United States, Germ and Chemical War Criminal 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- June 25 is the day when the U.S. imperialists started a war of aggression in Korea.
 Though half a century has passed, the Korean people still vividly remember the criminal biochemical warfare the U.S. imperialists committed against the peaceable inhabitants and cities in gross violation of the international law during the Korean war (June 25, 1950-July 27, 1953).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The aggressors launched germ and chemical warfare in the northern half of Korea during the war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In autumn of 1950, the U.S. Headquarters of Joint Chiefs of Staff worked up a plan to use the germ weapons in battles extensively. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 According to the plan, the aggressors applied germ weapons against the peaceful civilians and cities in a wicked way. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In the period from the beginning of January to April, 1952, they dropped various kinds of germ bombs in 169 areas in the northern half of Korea on 804 times and innumerable things and goods contaminated with poisonous insects and bacteria in more than 90 cities and counties on over 900 times. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. imperialists used more than 20 kinds of germ weapons during the war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They conducted even experiments on living-bodies with bacteria. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In 1951 they committed over 3,000 experiments on Korean people with germ weapons on warships not far off Wonsan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Another diabolical crime of the U.S. imperialists was that they used chemical weapons, a mass destruction weapon. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 From February 1951 to July 1953, they used many chemical weapons in 24 cities and counties of the northern half of Korea including Kangwon and Hwanghae provinces and on battlefields. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In particular, they released more than 15 million napalm bombs on military positions on the front and peaceful cities and farming and fishing villages in the rear. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. imperialists perpetrated even bio-chemical warfare unprecedented in the world history of war to achieve their aggressive purpose.

Kim Jong Il's Work Published in Kyrgyzstan 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- General Secretary Kim Jong Il's work "Let Us Carry Out the Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung's Instructions for National Reunification" was brought out in pamphlet by the Yvsh-Ata Publishing House of Kyrgyzstan.
 The work, published on Aug. 4, Juche 86 (1997), deals with the immortal exploits performed by President Kim Il Sung in the cause for national reunification and formulates the three principles of national reunification, the proposal for founding the Democratic Federal Republic of Koryo and the ten-point programme of the great unity of the whole nation as the three charters for national reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The manager of the publishing house said at a book releasing ceremony held on June 15 that this famous work serves as political pabulum instilling strength and courage into the world progressives. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Il Sung's instructions for national reunification are being successfully fulfilled by Kim Jong Il, lodestar of reunification, he noted, expressing belief that Korea would surely shine as a reunified and prosperous, great powerful nation under the leadership of Kim Jong Il.

Kim Jong Il Praised as Outstanding Statesman 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- Seminars, round-table talks and film shows were held in Russia, Austria and the Czech Republic between June 8 and 15 on the occasions of the 42nd anniversary of Kim Jong Il's start of work at the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea and 6th anniversary of the publication of the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration.
 The chairperson of the Party for Peace and Unity of Russia said at the seminar that Kim Jong Il's outstanding organizational ability, perseverance in practical activities and creative wisdom have brought about significant changes constantly in politics, military affairs and economy in the DPRK, adding that his feats for the world are really great. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The secretary of the Left Bloc of the Austrian Trade Union Federation noted at the round-table talks that the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration provided by the Songun politics of Kim Jong Il is the most realistic reunification program making it possible to prevent a war on the Korean Peninsula in the present time and achieve peaceful reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The chairman of the Czech Group for the Study and Materialization of the Juche Idea stated at the round-table talks that it is entirely thanks to the prominent and tested leadership of Kim Jong Il that DPRK has wrought historical miracles and made a long drive in the teeth of evermore undisguised moves of the U.S. imperialists to isolate and stifle it further.

Direct Talks between DPRK and U.S. Urged 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- Voices accusing the U.S. administration of its Korea policy and calling for DPRK-U.S. direct talks for a solution to the nuclear issue are growing louder in the U.S. political circles these days.
 Former U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Armitage in an interview with the Kyodo News of Japan criticized the Korea policy of Bush, advising the U.S. administration to put forward a package compensation proposal to the DPRK and promote negotiations on the nuclear issue. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 David Strube, former section chief for Korean affairs of the U.S. State Department, told a reporter that Bush was unwilling to have dialogue with the DPRK, judging from the abuses he hurled on its leadership. At the six-party talks, he noted, Bush insisted on the strategy of putting pressure on the DPRK while convincing it that it was "isolated" in the international community. But, in actuality, it is the U.S. and Japan that were isolated at the talks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He ridiculed the U.S. act of ignoring the reasoning of other countries participating in the six-party talks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 U.S. Senator Joseph Biden told a reporter that Bush's Korea policy had come a cropper. The U.S. needs to have direct talks with the DPRK for a solution to the nuclear issue, he said.

Egyptian Embassy Officials Help Korean Farmers 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- Egyptian Ambassador to the DPRK Moustafa Mohamed Ahmed Al Hatter and embassy officials Tuesday helped the Korea-Egypt Friendship Sosamjong Co-operative Farm in farming.
 After being briefed on the history of the farm to which President Kim Il Sung gave on-the-spot guidance, they helped the farmers in weeding a maize field. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 During break they appreciated an art performance given by farmers and talked with them, deepening friendly feelings. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The embassy officials handed aid materials to the farm.

Chokhwabi on Display at House of Class Education in Kaesong
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- Chokhwabi (a stone monument calling for rejection to friendship with invaders of the United States and European powers) was newly exhibited at the House of Class Education in Kaesong City, the DPRK. It was found out in the city.
 Similar monuments were erected in different parts of Korea in 1871. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It, made with natural granite, is 146 cm high, 43.2 cm wide and 27.5 cm thick. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Inscribed in bold strokes on the front side of the monument are the words "As Western barbarians invade the country, refusal to fight means friendship with them and pleading for friendship means selling off the nation". And carved in small letters beside them are words "These words were created in the year of Pyongin (1866) and monuments erected across the country in the year of Sinmi (1871). We warn this to our posterity".&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After the mid-1860s the Korean people had emerged victorious in battles for sinking the pirate ship General Sherman and for repulsing armed invaders of the U.S. and European countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On April 25, 1871, Taewongun (1820 - 1898), the then ruler of the feudal state of Ri Dynasty, saw to it that the monuments were erected in Seoul and other towns of the country. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Most of the monuments, however, were destroyed by the Japanese imperialist aggressors and Queen Min and other reactionary ruling quarters who were flunkeyists and capitulationists between 1882 and 1915. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The visitors to the house realize once again that the true nature of the U.S.-led imperialists will never change and harden their will to wipe out the aggressors once and for all.

Tomundaejak, Old Cookbook
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 21 (KCNA) -- Tomundaejak was written by Ho Gyun, a famous poet and novelist in Korea, in 1611.
 Tomundaejak is interpreted by the meaning that one tastes dishes cooked by restaurants. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The book introduces in detail data on the foodstuffs that were widely used in the dietary life of the Korean people at that time and famous local products. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The author, in the preface, notes that as there are many delicacies in Korea which has abundant local products for many mountains and seas on its three sides, he wrote the book for the purpose of conveying them to the generations to come. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The book is largely divided into four parts--fruit, meat, fish and vegetable. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The fruit part gives the various species of fruits including chestnut and jujube abundant in the country along with their producing areas. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Featuring in the meat part are various kinds of meat good for health including bear plantar, leopard funiculus, deer tail and pheasant and their producing areas. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The fish part introduces over 40 kinds of fishes including gray mullet, crucian carp, shad fish, killifish, codfish, sweetfish, mackerel, shellfish and crab, their producing areas and even their tastes. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Carried in the vegetable part are 26 kinds of vegetables including ginger and mustard and their producing centers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In the last part, the book gives the names of places famous with tea, spirits, sweet rice dish and so on, and the names and varieties of foodstuffs according to each season. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The book is of very significance in studying the dietary life of the Korean people.
